NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|North should not duck the SA. There are several reasons on this hand why the duck is wrong.|
PG| ***** 141 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|First of all, since South led the @H9, North knows that South does not have the @HJ (he would have led low from Jxx and J from Jx) and has at most a doubleton (South leads count in partner's unsupported suit). So there is some chance of a heart ruff.|
PG| ***** 142 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, there are some defensive complications. East has both the @HJ and @H10 (based on the @H9 lead) and may be able to throw a diamond loser on the 3rd heart. So the defense needs to take their diamond tricks before giving up the lead. |
PG| ***** 143 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Therefore, North, after playing the @SA, should lead the @DA and see what South signals. If he signals high, indicating the king (which is what he will do on this hand), North should then lead a 2nd diamond. That is 3 tricks for the defense. North has to hope that South will lead a club to give him a ruff for down 1.|
PG| ***** 144 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Note that if South had the @DK but also started with a singleton heart, he should signal with a low diamond even though he has the @DK. Then North will likely play a heart, and South would get his ruff and then could still cash the @DK.|
PG| ***** 145 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The point here is you should not duck an ace unless you have a good reason to. And on this hand, the defensive timing in fact says North should take her ace as soon as possible. |
PG| ***** 146 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This gives the defense several chances to beat the hand with potential diamond winners and heart and club ruffs. By ducking the ace, North gives up the chance for her side to get some ruffs and also gives declarer the chance to throw away a diamond on the third heart. So ducking the @SA will likely cost the defense at least one or two tricks.|
