NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|My philosophy is you should not bid grand slam unless you have better than 70% chance of making it. Here it turns out that because of the way the 2 hands fit, the 7@S grand slam is a very good contract. However, my philosophy is to never bid a grand slam unless I can pretty much count 13 tricks. |
PG| ***** 175 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The reason is that you will score well just for bidding a small slam. So if you bid a grand slam that goes down, you turned a good result into a very bad result. It is not worth the risk.|
PG| ***** 176 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Mathematically, it turns out you should not bid a grand slam that has less than about a 70% chance of making. That means that bidding a grand slam that simply depends on a 3-2 break (68%) is somewhat iffy. |
PG| ***** 177 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|From a practical perspective, it is almost always impossible to calculate whether or not you have a 70+% chance of making 7.. So my practical rule is I never bid 7 unless I can count 13 sure tricks. |
